Rating: 3
As written the recipe IS very bland, which if you've been to the UK means it's very traditional. I made these changes to make the dish tastier and eliminate the soupiness and, er, "after effects" that other reviewers noted: * I used half water and red wine for the gravy as previously suggested. I used two parts lamb and one part very lean ground round, which didn't affect the flavor but made the dish healthier. I also substituted diced carrots for half of the peas and used baby portobella mushrooms rather than simple white ones. * The recipe calls for no salt (!) and only one addition of pepper. Instead, I added salt and pepper to taste to the mushroom mixture, meat, and mashed potatoes so that everything would be balanced. I also added a dash of crushed red pepper to the meat with the peas and, taking a cue from a local Irish pub that makes a great version of this dish, I added curry powder to taste. I didn't measure but the idea was to have the curry add depth that would be detectable after a bite or two, not to overwhelm the dish. I added maybe 1 1/2 teaspoons. * When you saute the mushrooms, be sure that most of the liquid they give off during cooking has evaporated before proceeding. Also, ground lamb is usually very fatty and gives off a lot of liquid as it cooks. The recipe easily allows you to partly drain the meat after browning, eliminating the soupiness (and the noisy after effects, I suspect). If you still find the finished meat mixture is soupy, just simmer it until most of the liquid is gone. * To make the potato topping crisp and more visually pleasing, broil the dish briefly before serving. Set the rack in the middle of thge oven and keep an eye on it to make sure it doesn't burn. (It took about 2 minutes in my oven.)

