This is an easy and delicious weeknight meal and a different change of pace. Try topping it with "buttery mashed SWEET POTATOES" instead of using white potatoes. You could bake fresh sweet potatoes in the microwave, but I just used a large can of sweet potatoes, well drained. I then heated them in a large bowl in the microwave until they were hot as the butter melts easier and they mash better when they're not cold. I added a Tbsp. of brown sugar and seasoned them with salt and pepper. Proceed as the recipe directs.

Rating: 0
A good recipe for someone who doesn't have much prep time. The amount of mushrooms called for, however, is greater than usually used in a meat pie, and I personally think that the mushrooms overwhelm the lamb. Also, unless you are grinding the lamb yourself, you should be aware that you may need to drain off fat--some ground lamb is quite fatty. Lots of people do make this dish with leftover roast lamb or leftover roast beef. (The latter is like the French "hachis parmentier.") Home cooks in Britain add whatever they like by way of vegetables, especially of root vegetales, or no vegetables at all. When made with ground beef instead of lamb the concoction is often called "cottage pie." I suggest that if you use ground beef, you cook the meat until all the liquid it produces is gone--as Lydia Bastianich does when using ground beef. Finally, as a reviewer of the other shepherd's pie recipe on this site says, let's remember that shepherd's pie is a traditional dish, subject to variation, and really quite simple. Using stout as a reviewer or two suggest, by the way, is simply not traditional in England and does not sound like an enhancement to the dish.

